## Forward Euler

Now consider
$$
\begin{align*}
u(0 ) &= c \\
u'(x) - Î±(x) u(x) &= f(x)
\end{align*}
$$

**Definition (Restriction matrices)**
Define the $n-1 Ã— n$ _restriction matrices_ as
$$
\begin{align*}
    I_n^{\rm f} := \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ &â‹± \\ &&1 & 0 \end{bmatrix}\\
I_n^{\rm b} := \begin{bmatrix} 0 & 1 \\ &&â‹± \\ &&&1  \end{bmatrix} \\
\end{align*}
$$


Again we can replace the discretisation using finite-differences, giving us
$$
{u_{k+1} - u_k \over h} - Î±(x_k) u_k = f(u_k)
$$
for $k = 1,â€¦,n-1$. We need to add the term $Î±(x_k) u_k$ to our differential equation,
that is. We do this using the $n-1 Ã— n$ _(left) restriction matrix_ that takes a vector
evaluated at $x_1,â€¦,x_n$ and restricts it to $x_1,â€¦,x_{n-1}$,
as well as the $n Ã— n$ _multiplication matrix_
$$
A_n = \begin{bmatrix} Î±(x_0) \\ &â‹±\\&& Î±(x_n) \end{bmatrix}
$$
Putting everything together we have the system:
$$
\begin{bmatrix}
ğ_1^âŠ¤ \\
D_n -  I_n^{\rm L}  A_n
\end{bmatrix} ğ®^n = \underbrace{ \begin{bmatrix}
1 \\
-Î±(x_0)-1/h & 1/h\\
& \ddots & \ddots \\
&& -Î±(x_{n-1})-1/h & 1/h
\end{bmatrix}}_L ğ®^n = \begin{bmatrix} c \\ I_n^{\rm f} ğŸ \end{bmatrix}
$$
where $ğŸ = \begin{bmatrix} f(x_0) \\ â‹® \\ f(x_n) \end{bmatrix}$.

```julia
a = -1
c = 0
n = 2000
x = range(0, 1; length=n+1)
h = 1/n
A = Bidiagonal([1; fill(1/h, n)], fill(-a-1/h, n), :L)

norm(A \ [1; zeros(n)] - exp.(a*x),Inf)
```

Note that this is a simple forward-substitution of a bidiagonal system,
so we can also just construct it directly:
$$
\begin{align*}
u_1 &= c \\
u_{k+1} &= u_k + h a(x_k) u_k + h f(x_k)
\end{align*}
$$


**Remark (advanced)** Note this can alternatively be reduced to an integral
$$
u(t) = c \hbox{e}^{a t} + \hbox{e}^{a x} \int_0^x f(t) \hbox{e}^{-a t} \hbox d t
$$
and solved as above but this approach is harder to generalise.


## Backward Euler


Backward Euler is a small modification where we replace the forward-difference with a backward-difference,
that is
$$
{u_k - u_{k-1} \over h} - a(x_k) u_k = f(u_k)
$$
This leads to the system:
$$
\begin{bmatrix}
ğ_1^âŠ¤ \\
D_n -  I_n^{\rm R}  A_n
\end{bmatrix} ğ®^n = \underbrace{ \begin{bmatrix}
1 \\
-Î±(x_1)-1/h & 1/h\\
& \ddots & \ddots \\
&& -Î±(x_{n-1})-1/h & 1/h
\end{bmatrix}}_L ğ®^n = \begin{bmatrix} c \\ I_n^{\rm R} ğŸ \end{bmatrix}
$$


```julia
c = 0
n = 20
x = range(0, 1; length=n+1)
h = 1/n
L = Bidiagonal([1; fill(1/h-a, n)], fill(-1/h, n), :L)
```

```julia
norm(L \ [1; zeros(n)] - exp.(a*x),Inf)
```

Again this is a bidiagonal forward-substitution:
$$
\begin{align*}
u_1 &= c \\
(1 - h a(x_{k+1})) u_{k+1} &= u_k + h f(x_{k+1})
\end{align*}
$$
That is,
$$
u_{k+1} = (1 - h a(x_{k+1}))^{-1}(u_k + h f(x_{k+1}))
$$



## Systems of equations

We can also solve systems, that is, equations of the form:
$$
\begin{align*}
ğ®(0) &= ğœ \\
ğ®'(x) - A(x) ğ®(x) &= ğŸ(x)
\end{align*}
$$
where $ğ®(x) âˆˆ â„^d$ and $A(x) âˆˆ â„^{d Ã— d}$.
We again discretise at the grid $x_k$
by approximating $ğ®(x_k) â‰ˆ ğ®_k âˆˆ â„^d$.
This can be reduced to a block-bidiagonal system as in
the scalar case which is solved via forward-substitution. Though
it's easier to think of it directly. 

Forward Euler gives us:
$$
\begin{align*}
ğ®_1 &= c \\
ğ®_{k+1} &= ğ®_k + h A(x_k) ğ®_k + h ğŸ(x_k)
\end{align*}
$$
That is, each time-step consists of matrix-vector multiplication.
On the other hand:
$$
\begin{align*}
ğ®_1 &= c \\
ğ®_{k+1} &= ğ®_k + h A(x_k) ğ®_k + h ğŸ(x_k)
\end{align*}
$$


